[2.1 Structure of Relational Databases]
	- relational database consists of a collection of "tables"
		-> unique name

	- row in a table represents a "relationship" among set of values.

	- tuple : sequence of values
		-> relationship between n values is represented by an n-tuple of values.

	* "relationship" is used to refer to a table

	* "tuple" is used to refer to a row

	* "attribute" refers to a column of a table

	- "relation instance" -> refer to a specific instance of a relation, that is, containing a specific set of rows.

	- "domain": set of permitted values for each attribute of a relation
		-> "atomic" if elements of the domain are considered to be indivisible units.

	- "null value"
		-> unknown value or does not exist

